Life motto: there’s no such thing as too much butter.

These chicken tenders are a family staple and after you make them, you’ll see why.

Here’s what you need:

One pound of chicken tenderloins 
1/3 a cup of mayo (ish)
A couple tablespoons of mustard (ish)
A tablespoon of brown sugar (ish)
A sleeve of ritz crackers (crushed)
A stick of butter (the real stuff)

Here’s what you do:
I create an assembly line of the chicken tenders, followed by a dish of the honey mustard mixture, followed by a dredging station of the ritz crackers with melted butter.

Place the dressed chicken tenders in a greased baking sheet and cook at 375 for about 35 min or until golden brown and serve hot. We love it with green beans, Mac ‘n cheese, and a honeyed biscuit like the southern folk we are (also delicious straight out of the oven). Tell me if you try it! 😘

scrolling through a million voices telling you that next year you can be skinnier, richer, stronger or whatever the current (and subjective) definition of “better” may be.

Something I’ve learned (and re-learned) a time or two is this: there’s a lot of power in celebrating who you are right now.

In this minute.

Without changing a darn thing.

And, wait for it … LIKING that person. 

Something tells me there’s probably a whole lotta good in who you are in this exact season despite what this world will try to convince you.

Today as you’re encouraged to make your list of resolutions at what you need to change, maybe turn the page and write down all the qualities or accomplishments or skills you appreciate in yourself. And then read them over a couple times.

A bittersweet thing about death is all the stories being told that you’ve never heard until someone you love passes away. Hard memories or conflict seem to fade and so many sweet and special things about your loved one tend to bubble up and shine bright.

Over the last week or so as our Memaw was placed on Hospice we’ve recounted so much of the good we’ve seen in her life and God’s faithfulness that has been evident through all 81 years.

Memaw was an independent woman in every sense of the word. She was a pioneer in real estate for women in central Arkansas, loved her country music and Gospel hymns, and always had a deep appreciation for beauty.

I played for hours and hours at her desk growing up and she taught me how to navigate TJ Maxx like a pro. She truly championed and probably oversold me in a few areas, but I know that shaped so much of who I am.

About ten years ago, a massive stroke stole much of her independent spirit, but she eventually responded with a humility and a softness that truly became the most beautiful thing about her. I can only hope that I allow for that same beauty from ashes in hard things in my own life.

It’s been an honor to celebrate her the last few days and do all the remembering. My home is filled with framed pictures of her today from the family gathering we hosted yesterday. This morning as I’ve sipped coffee from her wedding china, walked through all the picture memories and had Blessed Assurance on repeat, I’m so grateful for Memaw and all she was. She was a good one.

Simple, savory and delicious, this healthy dinner is one you want to save! Def making this again.

Salmon Power Bowls

Here’s what you NEED:
* 2 salmon filets
* Salt and freshly ground black pepper
* Extra-virgin olive oil
* 1 sweet potato, cut into ¾-inch cubes
* 1 cup broccoli florets, fresh or frozen
* 2 teaspoons ground ginger, divided 
* 1/4 teaspoon cinnamon 
* ½ teaspoon ground turmeric, divided
* ½ teaspoon garlic powder, divided
* 2 teaspoons honey
* 1 cup cooked quinoa or rice
* ½ avocado, sliced
* Spicy Mayo if you’re into that 
* Everything but the Bagel Seasoning

Here’s what you DO:
1. Preheat oven to 450F.
2. Arrange sweet potatoes on one half of sheet pan, broccoli on other half. Drizzle both with olive oil and season with salt & pepper. Sprinkle sweet potatoes with 1 teaspoon ginger and ¼ teaspoon turmeric. Sprinkle broccoli with ¼ teaspoon garlic powder. Roast for 10 minutes until crispy.
 3. Transfer finished potatoes and broccoli to a plate and set aside. Arrange salmon skin side down and drizzle with olive oil, honey, 1 teaspoon ginger, ¼ teaspoon garlic powder, ¼ teaspoon turmeric, and salt & pepper. Broil for 5 minutes, or until browned on top and flaked easily with a fork.
 
5. Divide warm quinoa/rice between two serving bowls, then top with sweet potatoes and broccoli. Place a fillet onto each bowl. I topped with avocado,  spicy mayo and everything but the bagel seasoning and it was 🤌.

Sherried Tomato Soup (thank you Pioneer Woman! 🥳)

** i didn’t complete my thought in the video- bring the first batch of ingredients to a boil and then TURN OFF the heat before adding in the delicious sherry and cream!!

Here’s what you need:
* 6 tbsp. Melted Butter
* 1 whole Medium Onion, Diced
* 1 bottle (46 Oz.) Tomato Juice
* 2 cans (14 Oz. Cans) Diced Tomatoes
* 1 tbsp. (up To 3 Tablespoons) Chicken Base
* 3 tbsp. (up To 6 Tablespoons) Sugar
* 1 pinch Salt
* Black Pepper To Taste
* 1 c. Cooking Sherry
* 1 1/2 c. Heavy Cream
* Chopped Fresh Parsley
* Chopped Fresh Basil

Here’s what you do:
Sauté diced onions in butter until translucent. Then add canned tomatoes, tomato juice, chicken base, sugar, pinch of salt, black pepper and stir. Bring to a near boil, then turn off heat. Add in sherry and cream and stir. Add in parsley and basil to taste.

1. First, it feels like you are working hard and don’t feel like the income is reflecting the time you’re putting in.
2. Eventually it shifts and you realize the time/effort you’re putting into your business seems to be a fair exchange. 
3. Then it shifts AGAIN and it feels like you’re being compensated MORE than the time and effort you’re putting in (my fav part).

But people get frustrated in that first part and as soon as it gets hard think it means they’re not cut out for it or the work isn’t worth it and they bail (usually claiming it’s the company or model’s fault) instead of getting coached and developing skill sets on how to improve progress. It’s more about being able to see the long term affects and becoming willing to do the hard for long term RESULTS.

And not everyone will do it. Just like everything else in life. But as I sat around a board room full of SUPER SMART people we talked about how to make this an even BETTER opportunity for the people that ARE wanting to go all the way with this. Our Exec team is laser focused on helping people make significant money from home by partnering with a brand you can feel GREAT about.

Have you had moments in life where you’re just completely overwhelmed with God’s goodness and beauty and GRANDEUR? Maybe looking at an incredible view, listening to beautiful music or just feeling really really loved. 

This whole beach day I couldn’t shake that feeling. It was next level. I would randomly cry at how my perception of beauty seemed to have been tugged and stretched to hold an entirely new definition. One I couldn’t see before, but saw so clearly then.

“This is definitely in the top three things you’ve ever made.” -@elifowlkes on his second helping of these super yum Caribbean Jerk Chicken Bowls 

This was light, refreshing and REAL good! I’ll definitely be making it again!

🌶️ I will say the marinade is a little on the spicier side, so you may want to cut it if that isn’t your thing.

What you need:
1 lb Chicken Breast, cut into chunks 
Caribbean Jerk Marinade 
2 Sweet Potato, peeled and diced
Turmeric 
Brown Sugar
Garlic Salt
Paprika
Cumin
Cinnamon
Olive oil
Avocado oil
Red pepper, diced or thinly sliced
2 avocados peeled, seeded, mashed
Mango, peeled and sliced around the pit
1/2 a red onion, diced
2 limes
2 cups of rice
Garlic
1 15oz can of red beans, drained

What you do:
Cover diced chicken in marinade and let sit in fridge for at least 30 minutes. 

Preheat oven to 425
Toss sweet potatoes in 1 tbsp avocado oil with a few dashes each of garlic salt, paprika, tumeric, cumin, cinnamon and brown sugar. Roast on middle rack about 30 minutes. Set aside. 

To make coconut rice: sauté garlic in olive oil and then add in rice to toast a couple minutes or so before adding in one can of coconut milk and 1 can of red beans. Add juice of one lime and tablespoon of cilantro. I used minute rice here (😆😆😆) so I just brought to a bowl and then removed and removed from heat. I’m quite confident there’s fancier ways to do it … but this was my method. Next time I’ll add some toasted coconut here too!

To cook the chicken, I drained off the marinade, added a little olive oil to my skillet and then cooked over medium heat until cooked through. It was about 4-5 minutes on each side. The last few minutes you can add the red peppers OR eat raw if you want the extra crunch (I do!).

To make the smashed avocado I just peeled, seeded and smashed the avocado before adding a sprinkle of garlic salt and juice of one lime. 

Then you just layer these up to your heart’s content: I started with the coconut rice and beans, added chicken, sweet potato, smashed avocado, red onion, mango, red pepper and then topped with cilantro. 🤌🏼

You’re going to love this. 🤗

Do you ever think back to your childhood and the memories that stand out most and then wonder which ones will shine particularly bright in the memories your own kids?

I’m constantly thinking about that. 

I scroll through the thousands of pictures on my phone and think “what will they remember most about these days?”

I’ve been listening to a book on “habits of the household” this week on my walks and this quote made me rewind and listen a couple more times.

“The most significant thing about any household is what is considered normal.”

He went on to say “it’s the normal that shapes us the most, even though we notice it the least.”

I’ve been thinking about what’s normal over here … the tone of how we talk to each other, how we eat together, how it FEELS in our house… it’s all our own little version of normal.

In a weird way it takes the pressure off. It’s never really the big birthday parties or lavish gifts or grand displays of affection. 

It’s the repeated little things that create trust and safety and “home” to all your little people: that someone is asking about the things important to them, that they have clean clothes to wear, how you remember their favorite snack at the grocery store, that they sit and hear how their siblings days went at the dinner table … not the big, but the small. 

Not things you’ve done once or twice, but things you DO on a daily basis. 

That’s helpful for me to think about too.

Summer time can bring new rhythms in our homes. A lot more togetherness, different routines and different “normals.”

These ordinary days are shaping the normals of the people in our homes. That can feel like pressure or it can feel like the sweetest gift we can give!

Blueberry Banana Muffins

what you need:
* 3 bananas, large and ripe
* 1/2 c sugar 
* 1 egg, slightly beaten
* ⅓ c butter melted
* 1 c blueberries
* 1 tsp baking soda
* 1 tsp baking powder
* ½ tsp salt
* 1 ½ c flour

what you do:
* In a mixing bowl, mash ripe bananas then add sugar and egg.
* Next add melted butter and fresh blueberries.
* Combine flour, baking soda, salt, baking powder and fold into banana mix.
* Scoop mix into well greased muffin cups.
* Bake at 375 degrees for 20 minutes.
* Makes 12 large muffins or 24 mini muffins (decrease amount of time for mini muffins).
* Sprinkle a little sea salt on the top for love if you’re into that

Dusted off the crock pot and made chili mac and cornbread before football tonight. It was a hit!

Here’s what you NEED:
* 1 pound ground beef
* 1 small onion, chopped
* 4 cloves garlic, minced
* 2 (15-16 oz) cans chili beans in chili sauce
* 1 (28 oz) can crushed tomatoes
* 1 (15 oz) can diced tomatoes
* 2 cups beef broth
* 1 tablespoon chili powder
* ½ teaspoon cumin
* salt and pepper to taste
* 8 ounces elbow macaroni (I subbed chickpea pasta for this and no one knew the difference), uncooked
* 2 cups of baby spinach, chopped 
* 1 cup sharp cheddar, shredded
* Desired toppings: cheddar,sour cream, green onions, cornbread …

Here’s what you DO:
* Brown ground beef and drain grease. Add to a 6 qt slow cooker or larger and stir in remaining ingredients EXCEPT for the pasta. 
* Cover and cook for 4 hours on HIGH or 8 hours on LOW. In the last 15 minutes of cooking stir in the uncooked pasta and cover. Stir and test to see if pasta is to your liking. However, even with the slow cooker off the pasta will continue to cook just from the heat of the chili and crock itself so unless your pasta is really chewy or crunchy I strongly suggest only cooking it for the last 15 minutes of cook time.
* Before serving fold in chopped spinach and cheddar cheese
* Serve immediately with desired toppings. Enjoy!

MEDITERRANEAN CHICKEN ORZO BOWL

If you‘re looking for a simple way to add some YUM to your weeknight dinner menu, this is it!

Here’s what you NEED
2 lbs chicken breast
1 Tbl butter
1 Tbl Greek Seasoning, divided
3 Tbl EVOO, divided
12 oz arugula 
1/4 cup of your fav vinaigrette 
1 block Boursin garlic + herb cheese
16 oz orzo pasta, uncooked
3 cloves of garlic, chopped 
1/2 cup sun-dried tomatoes, chopped
1/2 cup Kalamata olives, chopped
1/2 cup toasted pine nuts
4 cups of broth
2 cups spinach 
1/2 cup Parmesan cheese
1/2 cup of parsley, chopped

Here’s what you DO:
•Preheat oven to 425
•Place Boursin cheese in the center of a large baking dish
•Add orzo, sun-dried tomatoes, olives, garlic, pine nuts and broth to the dish, then drizzle a couple tablespoons of EVOO over the top.
•Cover dish with foil and bake for 30 min, stirring (I didn’t disrupt the cheese) after 15 minutes. 
•after 30 minutes, remove foil, stir completely and fold in spinach and Parmesan. Bake uncovered an additional 5-10 minutes. 

While pasta bakes, cook the chicken on the stove. My forever fav way to cook chicken is
•add 1 tbl butter and 1 tbl EVOO to skillet on med heat
•slice dry chicken breast length ways for thinner pieces. Sprinkle with Greek seasoning (I use the cavenders brand). 
•add to skillet and cook 5-6 on each side, until center is opaque. 

For arugula, simply toss 12-16 ounces of arugula with 1/4 cup your favorite vinaigrette 

To plate, place the arugula in pasta bowl or plate, top with pasta dish and place chicken breast and add chopped parsley for garnish if you’re into that. 

I hope you love it as much as we did!

Lesson learned from a decade of building an online business with children underfoot:

5 things that have helped me to be intentional with my time and focus (because it seems I could always use more of both!)

▪️Prioritize tasks: I usually brain dump what needs to get done the following week over the weekend. Sunday afternoon I pull out my calendar and add the to-do’s in where I’m going to actually get said tasks done. Otherwise I just keep picking the easy/fun tasks and skip right over the not-so-fun.
▪️ Create a schedules: the more systems/routines I have, the more the habits just seamlessly happen. They go from things I’ve done once or twice to just what I DO on a daily business, a part of who I am! 🟡 Pro-Tip: add “catch up” time to your calendar so when a kid gets sick or needs a snuggle sesh or you need a human minute, you’ve got time built in to pick back up where you were interrupted.
▪️Learn to say no: to yourself, your kids, or the endless barrage of “shoulding” in your brain. Saying no can be seasonal, there’s some things that may be a no now, but you can pick back up later. 
▪️ Self-care: Put time on your calendar to be a human- read, walk, pray, nap … whatever it is. Give yourself some margin to rest and recharge- this allows you to be so much more productive in the working times.
▪️ Stay flexible: Dishwashers are going to go out, kids are going to need to be picked up early from school or a friend is going to call and need a listening ear. Having those extra time blocks in your calendar and not overcommitting allows you to know it’s all going to be okay. Because it is.

From one ambitious mama to another- you got this. You really do.

here’s what you NEED:
2.5 lb chuck roast 
salt and pepper
1/2 package of good taco seasoning 
1/2 onion, sliced or diced 
3 large garlic cloves 
2 sprigs fresh oregano 
17 oz bone broth (I use Kettle and Fire)
creamy salsa (recipe below)
avocado 
raw or pickled red onion

here’s what you DO:
•preheat oven to 350
•start with chuck roast in an oven safe dish that has a lid
•season both sides of the roast with a couple punches of salt and pepper and the 1/2 packet of taco seasoning 
•cut up your large onion, garlic cloves with springs of oregano or thyme if using 
•pour in your beef broth
•cover, then place in oven for three hours. If your roast is more than 2.5 lbs, then the aim for about an hour per pound, plus 30 min. So if your roast is 3 lbs, 3.5 hours, etc. 
•after 3 hours, remove the chuck roast from the oven, shred using two forks, mix well with the drippings, then put back in the pan at 425 for 45 minutes to an hour. Can you see why this comes out so tender?!

To make the sauce, in a small food processor add 4 heaping tablespoons of thick Greek yogurt, 1/2 cup salsa, the juice of one lime and a couple pinches of salt. Taste and adjust as needed. 

Plate up however your heart desires, we served with rice, the beef, avocado, red onions and the sauce.

Is there anything worse than small talk? Yes, there is. It’s small talk with people whom you are connected to, but really don’t know that much about. In a season of loneliness where people feel disconnected and like they’re really not seen or heard, I LOVED these table-starter questions from @julie.majors.kentucky e-mail newsletter a couple weeks ago. Fight the urge to think this wouldn’t work for your family, or it could be awkward and instead start a tradition of meaningful conversations around your family table (or living room with paper plates on your laps).

It might end up being your favorite memory of the whole day!

Here’s some of the cards I added inspired by Julie’s recommendations:

1. What Thanksgiving memories come to mind about your childhood?
2. What’s something you got in trouble for as a kid?
3. What defines a good vacation?
4. What motivates you to work hard?
5. How do you rest or recharge?
6. What is one word a friend would use to describe you?
7. What energizes you?
8. What are/were your mother’s best qualities? your father’s?
9. What’s something you had as a child that today’s kids are missing out on?
10. What’s a passion project you’re working on?
11. What’s a Thanksgiving tradition you love and want to pass down as well?

Happy, happy Thanksgiving, friends!!
